AB  - The geographic center of El Ni & ntilde;o has shifted from the tropical eastern Pacific (EP) in the 20th century to the tropical central Pacific (CP) in the 21st century. Analyzing data spanning 1948-2018, this study uncovers notable alterations in the impact of the changing El Ni & ntilde;o patterns on California market squid (Doryteuthis opalescens) landings. While the traditional EP El Ni & ntilde;o in the 20th century significantly reduces squid landings, this impact diminishes with the ascent of the CP type of El Ni & ntilde;o in the 21st century. Remarkably, the CP-I type of El Ni & ntilde;o, a specific variant where warming occurs predominantly in the central Pacific and is often less intense but more frequent than traditional El Ni & ntilde;o events, can even amplify squid landings. These transformations stem from variations in sea surface temperature, trade winds, and Sverdrup transport associated with different El Ni & ntilde;o types. These findings suggest that the fishery community should consider developing adaptive approaches to address the evolving impacts of El Ni & ntilde;o.
