AB  - Statolith microstructure was analysed to infer age and describe the life history of Loliolus beka in the East China Sea, a dominant squid in the coastal ecosystem. Size-at-age data were obtained from 622 individuals that were collected monthly in the inshore area from 2019 to 2020. Ages ranged from 59-116 days, suggesting L. beka has a short lifespan of about four months. The back-calculated hatching time showed that L. beka hatch continuously throughout the whole year, with three alternating hatching cohorts. Significant differences in life histories were detected among the three hatching cohorts; autumn cohort showed a higher weight growth rate, while mantle length of spring cohort increased faster. The daily age information combining sliding window analysis provided further insight into the thermal conditions experienced during the life cycle of L. beka. The results revealed that the long-term warming trend in the East China Sea exceeded the preferred temperature range of L. beka and resulted in negative relationships with growth. The results provide an understanding of life history characteristics of L. beka, and could contribute to better understanding the flexibility and plasticity of L. beka under environmental changes and effective fisheries management.
