AB  - Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis, a commercially important cephalopod in China, exhibits distinct diurnal vertical movements and thrives in warm waters. We investigated the relationship between seawater temperature and S. oualaniensis abundance in the Northwest Indian Ocean (2017-2020) using Chinese squid fishery data. We analyzed temperature data from 0 to 300 m depths at 50 m intervals and calculated temperature differentials. Generalized Additive Models (GAM) predicted the fishery's spatial and temporal distribution. The optimal GAM explained 69.1% of the variance. Key contributors were latitude-longitude interactions (Lon, Lat), month, sea surface temperature (SST) T0, and seawater temperature (SWT) T200 at 200 m. The 50-100 m depth layer had the most influence. Fishing grounds were influenced by temperature variations and sea surface conditions. The optimal sea surface temperature range for S. oualaniensis was 27-30 degrees C, with prime areas at 58 degrees-64 degrees E and 14 degrees 19 degrees N. Seasonal variability was observed, with higher yields in fall and winter. The high-value area shifted northward over time. This GAM model improves predictions of S. oualaniensis distribution and demonstrates the impact of vertical temperature structures. It provides valuable insights for fishery production and offers a new approach for studying thermophilic species with vertical behaviors.
