TI  - Spatiotemporal Evolution and Driving Forces of Desertification in Typical Semi-Arid Regions of China Based on an ML Model
T2  - JOURNAL OF THE AMERICAN WATER RESOURCES ASSOCIATION
LA  - English
KW  - climate change and human activities
KW  - desertification dynamics
KW  - driving factors
KW  - machine learning
KW  - semi-arid ecosystems
KW  - NDVI
AB  - Land desertification, a major form of ecosystem degradation, poses severe ecological and socio-economic challenges worldwide. The Xiliao River Basin, located in the semi-arid agro-pastoral transition zone of northern China, has long suffered desertification, making it crucial to clarify its dynamics for ecological restoration. In this study, a Desertification Difference Index (DDI) was reconstructed at 5-year intervals from 1985 to 2025 by integrating Landsat imagery on Google Earth Engine (GEE) with an Albedo-NDVI feature space. Fifteen natural and socio-economic indicators were incorporated into an XGBoost model with SHAP interpretability to quantify nonlinear contributions and factor associations. Results show: (1) desertification intensified from 1985 to 2000, with degraded land expanding 2.74% annually, but reversed in 2001-2025, when recovery exceeded degradation at 3.01% annually; (2) strong spatial heterogeneity was evident, with degradation concentrated in the Horqin Sandy Land, while Chifeng and Tongliao showed recovery; (3) the model achieved high accuracy (test R-2 = 0.98). SHAP analysis indicated irrigation water use (21.2%), precipitation (15.7%), and grazing (13.5%) dominated 1985-2000, whereas precipitation (26.5%), cropland reduction (16.8%), and soil moisture (14.7%) were key in 2001-2025. These results reveal interactive mechanisms and temporal shifts between climate and human activities, supporting targeted ecological management in semi-arid regions.
