AB  - Above-Ground Biomass (AGB) is a critical indicator for monitoring vegetation and carbon dynamics. This is particularly true in agroforestry systems, where Above-ground biomass (AGB) reflects the potential carbon sequestration of trees integrated into agricultural landscapes, supporting climate change mitigation and sustainable land management. In this study, we used publicly available Sentinel-2 satellite data to map AGB in agroforestry systems, where the discontinuous tree canopy, designed to allow sunlight for understory crops, makes the spatial and temporal resolution of the sensor particularly well suited to capture the unique vegetation dynamics of this ecosystem. First, a convolutional neural network (CNN) enhanced by a convolution block attention module (CBAM), is pretrained with 30 000 patches using the high-resolution aerial light detection and ranging (LiDAR) acquired in The Netherlands as reference. The large-scale pretraining enables the model to effectively capture key features of Sentinel-2 for AGB estimation. The model is then tested, with and without fine-tuning, in four different agroforestry study areas in Africa and Latin America. Validation against reference airborne LiDAR data demonstrates strong generalization ability of the proposed approach with $R$$<^>{2}$ values of 0.79, 0.73, 0.82, and 0.81 for Tanzania, Colombia, Nicaragua, and Peru, respectively. Our findings highlight the potential of combining LiDAR-based structural information with deep transfer learning to support large-scale biomass estimation and carbon monitoring in smallholder agroforestry landscapes.
